Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo, Norway, to spend 26 hours there and become the fourth US president in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
The award, medal and check of $1.4 million will be given to him for his outstanding efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The White House chief and his wife Michelle will land in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and have a busy schedule.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who selected him in October from 172 individuals and 33 organisations.
The presidential couple's schedule then includes an interview with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
The visit will culminate in a solemn ceremony in the afternoon, when Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive the award, but only the third to be presented with the prize in the Committee's own hall.
The White House informed us in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan at the award ceremony.
The president doesn't want to avoid this topic because he's aware that he's getting this award for being a president who's waging war in two countries right now.
He stepped up the war effort just a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to point out.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for 10 million Swedish crowns (about 1.1 million euros).
He plans to donate it to charity but has not yet decided which one.
His busy schedule then took him and his wife to a banquet that included the King and Queen of Norway, the head of government, and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant to accept that price at first.
For example, he mentioned feeling that he was not fully deserving.
He also repeatedly stated that this is not a prize for him alone, but for all those who defend the same values as him.
From the very beginning of the announcement, he said that he would be "calling for action".
