Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is even comical that Barack Obama, a well-known and wise president, has made a determined effort to repeat the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered to be very simple.
When he finally let out his long-awaited doctrine, it turned out that he had copied it onto carbon paper from the Bush Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content with using the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: "A New Road Forward".
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending new reinforcements to a civil war-torn Iraq as "irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences".
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which was based on the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed, so much so that the newspapers at the moment do not mention Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but, objectively speaking, he left his successor with a far more favourable final position than could have been hoped for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who demanded an increase in the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even sharply criticized the reluctance of the White House despite the subordination habits.
He was asking for 40,000 men to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months, but for lack of a better option, he at least swindled the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
He succeeded in getting the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he had originally counted on 10,000.
What seems to be causing the most problems in the whole Obama strategy is his intention to withdraw the troops from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete the whole process within three years.
Many doubt that a halving of the increase will produce the same results as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is the exact opposite - no one is counted on and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, who are used to changing leaders from day to day as they see fit.
Political institutions, though formally established, will remain as a powder-for-the-eyes, behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly difficult to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups given the lack of clarity on the relations, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "state of emergency", which is the basic aim of the operation, does not seem very real.
The time horizon of Obama's strategy is puzzling by its voluntarism.
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and it is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and unrealistic heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for their "immediate return home" will bring about a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will view it as an indirect admission of American defeat.
The recent NATO summit showed that the European willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is heading in the wrong direction.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor which can radically alter the situation is the development of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the tightened sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult question of resolving the problem by military force.
It will have to be answered, for example, when, according to Obama, America will be able to withdraw its troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will lead to a dramatic reversal of the situation in Afghanistan.
The only problem for Obama is that he has three years until the presidential election and therefore still has enough time to devise a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a complete fiasco.
