Czech discovery: a substance that works on "hard" HIV viruses too
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the spread of the HIV virus in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality is, in some cases, overridden by the fact that the combination does not act as intensely on common variants of the virus as some drugs already available.
There is no cure for AIDS at present.
However, a combination of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from multiplying in the body can dramatically extend the lives of patients.
However, their consumption has a number of side effects.
Moreover, the suppression of this multiplication has the effect of developing so-called resistant viruses that no longer have any effect on medicines.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University, paves the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarbons act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are a combination of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a way different from any drugs used so far and therefore could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work led them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their binding to virus proteins.
Metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus by the HIV protease there would be no generation of mature infectious virus particles.
If the protease of HIV is stopped, the spread of the virus in the patient's body will also be stopped, explain the researchers in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In their work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable.
The efficacy of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in test tubes and on resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarbons on the current version of the enzyme is not as strong as on clinical drugs, but it is not weaker than on resistant versions against which current drugs are often ineffective.
