The UN Group has draft plans for reducing emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- so far characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- came back into the spotlight on Friday, due to the release of a paper highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations taking on most of the burden in the near term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles, as well as providing some guidance on the way forward.
But it was seen as a major step forward in the time-strapped negotiations, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
The report, written by a special UN task force, does not say how much the rich countries will give to the poor to cope with the ongoing and long-term global warming.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies might reduce their carbon output and what would be the upper limit of global temperature rise that policymakers would be willing to tolerate.
It gives a lot of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Washington representative of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN climate change executive secretary general Yvo de Boer described as "the complete picture".
It outlines the guidelines for a possible agreement whereby the industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while the major developing countries would, over the same period, reduce their own by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change -- to cope with floods and droughts or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, US representative at the climate negotiations, rejected any discussion of the need for greenhouse gas reductions by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts of the major emerging economies, if they were not financed by the developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is getting tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the main developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not stress enough to ensure that the reductions could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top US negotiator was either lacking in "common sense" or "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the US would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, gaps have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The battle is now more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States bickering over their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers are fighting over who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in their attempt to hold major emitters accountable for their actions.
It's really a game in which a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Advisor for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most key participants say that the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the European Commission's Climate Unit, said that the action of small island states has "put political pressure on the whole political process", partly because they are now unified and are asking emerging economies such as China and India to act.
The debate became urgent as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most of the outstanding issues before the heads of government could reach agreement.
High-level officials such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister got off their planes and rushed to the Bella Center building for closed-door meetings and briefings, so they could make claims that would be studied over the next week.
The real picture of the rally -- where 13,000 people are coming in and out of the convention center every day -- activists playing guitars performing nightly shows mocking countries they say are betraying each other and proposals are being written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the great, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
In Britain, the first train at 140 miles per hour will redefine Monday syndrome
At 5:13 Monday morning, a whistle will sound through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transportation revolution in Britain.
The country's first high-speed commuter train will reach 225 km/h, running from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister for Transport, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes aboard the first Javelin commuter train outside London.
He hopes that the new service will allow Britain to integrate into an international network of fast and reliable trains and will connect the major conurbations of the Midlands, the North and Scotland to London.
Small lost holes will become thriving suburbs, business travel times will be much shorter, and the shift from air and car to train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing road traffic congestion.
In theory, the three main political parties are in favour of this project.
But the £10 billion needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable battle over timing and fears of environmental hazards could slow Britain's high-speed lines.
According to The Times, High Speed Two (HS2), a company set up in January to produce a feasibility report for the government, will return its document to Lord Adonis on 30 December.
This will allow it to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next stage planned for the high-speed network.
The new line from London to the West Midlands will be drawn within five metres of the urban area and sites where the impact on the environment may be controversial.
In the countryside, the map will be drawn up to 25 metres of the final route.
It is also envisaged that HS2 will present three options for a larger high-speed network, going north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
The preferred options are highlighted in a Y-shaped configuration for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two at or near Birmingham, with one branch going west of the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another going north-east, towards Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will run through Scotland.
"It seems that this will be the best performance option", said one railway professional.
When it's finished, the travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours and 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to a current one-hour journey.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making the UK's network the fastest in the world.
The initial route is designed to allow trains of 400m in length and capable of carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can run on a London to Birmingham line.
A terminal capable of handling 20 000 passengers per hour would be needed.
Given the space constraints, it is planned that an existing station will be enlarged to accommodate the high-speed network.
Experts in the rail industry say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this option.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should go ahead, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean a final decision will not be made until a general election.
Even if he launches the machine, the network will have to be built piece by piece.
Trains will first be forced to run off existing high-speed lines on the railways north of Birmingham, keeping travel times between London and Scotland above three hours.
This seems to be the best way to ensure that trains and airplanes are in line, and is a reference point for the railway revolution.
