They are adopting, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioural theory, recently reactivated by American "neuroscience" and widely disseminated, unbeknownst to them, by the academic institutes and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to use the "levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr reassures managers in a posture of mechanistic governance, which is unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and measuring the factors of mobilisation
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the smooth functioning of modern enterprises requires the adoption of a finalist view of human behaviour.
It is to integrate into any reasoning or practice of governance a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it is clearly seen as a means of achieving part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At present, only the studies resulting from the National Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivation.
These studies have shown that they judge their company on the basis of a predetermined doxa which, through their perceived image of the company, enables them to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life projects.
By identifying and measuring these mobilising factors, business leaders can monitor, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resource management "in place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo speech: "Just War" is worthy of praise on the right for Obama
The American right on Friday welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo the day before, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
