The Cradle of the Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae looked like other carnivorous dinosaurs: this bipedal was about six feet [2.0 m] long and six feet [1.5 m] high, its hind limbs were strong, its elongated skull had sharp, curved teeth, its short arms ended in sickle claws, and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to display these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was then part of the emerging land of the supercontinent of Pangaea and was located near the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
It tells us about the relationship between relatives, the distribution of these and their characteristics.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating the site of Gohst Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a Triassic sedimentary layer.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have uncovered the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says that this is a remarkable discovery. The fossils of Triassic dinosaurs are extremely rare, limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not consider this discovery particularly spectacular, but he does say that it confirms some theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the very earliest dinosaurs.
Experts are wondering, among other things, when the saurians split into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores), which include the later tyrannosaur and velociraptor, and from which the birds, sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds, and their relatives, and the ornithischian herbivores, which include species such as the triceratops and the stegosaur, are descended.
According to studies by S. Nesbitt and colleagues, the Tawa was one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting mix of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found evidence that suggests the Tawa hallae had small air sacs in their bones at the level of the skull, just like the birds that are descendants of the theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe than for mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the huge sauropods also had air sacs and a lightweight skeleton, it is reasonable to assume that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers concluded that the Saurian had appeared there.
So the three major evolutionary lines split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, all the land that emerged to form the supercontinent of Pangaea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to him.
The researchers argue that the three species cannot descend from a common ancestor that migrated.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of the journal Science Studies says that there were at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a Bonn paleontologist, says that there is an even older species, the sillesaurus, that lived in what is now Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
He said that this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved whereas there are hardly any on other continents.
However, how dinosaurs, which came from a relatively rare collateral lineage of the reptile branch, managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary age, remains a mystery to this day.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today's crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread across the planet, fostering the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not permanent.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction event where dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have gone extinct.
Or maybe the dinosaurs were better adapted and so they were able to eliminate competition in the field.
At any rate, such success is not permanent.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite helped to develop a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and had been shadowed since: the mammals.
