The worlds of the dream
Some people wake up to see images and hear voices that no one else sees or hears.
It is not only in the case of the mentally ill or the drug-addicted that the boundaries between imagination and reality become blurred.
As long as these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is fine.
When we lie in our darkened rooms, we can indulge in the wildest dreams and fantasies without hindrance.
However, one who, while awake, experiences a dream state, hears and sees things that others do not perceive, is soon reputed in our Western world to be either insane or drugged, or at least to be an original.
Such images and voices do not appear only in the case of mentally ill persons or in the case of drug addicts.
It's our imagination that's at fault: it's the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint paint paintings, write novels, but sometimes causes the boundaries between dream, madness and reality to blur.
A conscious waking state, taking the form of a dream, can take on the most varied forms, in the best case we call it visions, in the worst case madness.
But even though the trigger and the effect are distinct, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the secondary states of shamans, psychosis and hallucinations are all attributable to very similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of neurotransmitters in the brain - primarily dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - is disturbed and the interaction between the different parts of the brain is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts are very common during schizophrenia.
The earth's gravitational pull no longer has any power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have been looking into the relationship between madness and dreams.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of waking dream; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 "a great resemblance between madness and dream"; for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
