75% of working mothers have had work-related problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to become mothers.
This is the finding of the study Fertility and women's career in Spain , carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their career restricted by motherhood.
The study shows that there are many differences in the beginning of married life and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of job she has.
Women who have no outside activity, work part-time or have a low-stable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
In contrast, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay marriage and first pregnancy and have fewer children.
Women aged 35 to 49 with a permanent job have their first child on average 3.7 years after they have settled down as a couple, rising to 4.1 for those in the public sector.  These data show that women with a permanent job have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to delay marriage and the arrival of children.
Moreover, the type of employment influences maternity to a large extent, but less the date of the beginning of the marriage, explains Margarita Delgado, a researcher at the CSIC.
The level of education is another factor which widen the gap between the age of marriage and the age of the first child.
The survey found that the higher the level of training, the more late they get married and have their first child.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with primary and secondary education became mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years respectively on average.
 Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed primary education marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those with intermediate or higher education reverse this programme and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child, Ms Delgado said.
