Emergency braking assistance is now compulsory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as will be the case with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already compulsory for newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while a waiting period has been set for the rest of the vehicles until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen pedestrian protection, although, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear-end collisions.
The emergency brake assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system by the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure on until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of drivers involved in an accident had not been able to apply the brake before the collision, and half of them had not used the brake to their full potential.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were fitted with these types of components, up to 1 100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularisation of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents involving injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system which, by means of a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device applies maximum effort to the brakes to minimize damage.
