New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car parks are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a disaster are brought back to a garage, where an expert must assess the damage and the cost of repairing them.
Each accident is different, and calculating the cost of parts and labour time can be a long and complex job.
Calculating the cost of a repair of between EUR 20 000 and EUR 30 000 by hand, including parts and labour, can take two or three hours.
However, with the help of the latest computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
That is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Providers of claims assessment and maintenance services and solutions are devoted to collecting information from manufacturers, processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the North American Solera group, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other competitors in the field of evaluation tools and the production of information on the sector are GTMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data supplied by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain has 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is constantly increasing, so that in the last five years more versions, variants and engine variants have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car comes on the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very difficult task, since each of the thousand parts of the vehicle must be catalogued and the price recorded.
In addition, a smart  graphic image is created of each model, which can be clicked on to the different parts of a passenger car.
If it is a mass-sold model, the work can be ready in a week if the process proceeds very quickly.
If it is a low-selling car, it may take three to four months.
For example, they have information on the most exclusive models, such as Porsche, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
For vehicles on the road, the figure is over 99%.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centres around the world (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which is specialised in a particular brand.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million a year in developing these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data is recorded, and customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this huge flow of information enables these companies to give it different uses and to offer a variety of products.
The most common application is for repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for handling broken parts or for calculating the value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that provides information on the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex doesn't offer it in our country, but they do it in the United States.
It is easy to see from the products offered by Audatex what kind of support it can provide to professionals in the sector.
The company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard claim assessment solution for experts.
These include cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, the calculation takes into account the manufacturer's estimated repair times or the painting schedules.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is €5.75 for customers who use it little, up to ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which carries out thousands of tests, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow complete identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it has been removed from the assembly line, only by its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle glass, and AudaSubastas is an open-source server on the Internet that allows for auctioning on vehicles declared as wrecked.
Its statistics service is very useful for identifying trends, carrying out geodemographic analyses or finding out about common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a given brand have gone to the garage for a breakdown or how many have suffered serious accidents over a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tool.
It sells, amongst other things, Gt Estimate, which is also aimed at experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the official parts, prices and times of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of claims, breakdowns or maintenance of buildings.
The Valuation Guide is a historical reference product on the market.
The company works with 24 000 users in garages, 3 100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has increased by 20% per year over the past three years, reaching EUR 10.8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it began its process of internationalisation, with the establishment of an office in Paris.
Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and moved to Spain in 1979.
According to company sources, 62% of its turnover is generated in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America.
The global turnover of the Solera group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) is expected to be $557 million, up 3.3% on 2008.
In our country, the company will receive EUR 19.1 million, which is 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, the Solera group was listed at $1 billion, today its shares are valued at a total of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, it has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and is a component of the Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
Internet auctions of damaged cars
Last October, the Solera Group bought Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of cars, motorcycles and special vehicles affected by disasters.
The operation involved a cost of EUR 59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could be increased next year to the remaining 15%.
The aim of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its clients, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This valuation and sales service is exclusively for professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, garages, cash registers and professional sellers who must be registered before they can start trading.
The platform was set up in Germany in 1996 and manages more than 650 000 transactions across Europe, including 500 000 in Germany.
Its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently over 1500 vendors and 4000 experts registered on the site.
It handles 3,000 ads a day and on the Spanish market, 100 new ads are published every day.
Under Spanish law, a car with a chassis number removed cannot be used, but some parts that are not damaged can be used as spare parts.
The collector's cars can be re-registered, even though they have been withdrawn, after complex procedures.
Four-stage garage cleaning
With the Auda-Taller tool, Audatex ensures that the user gets a quote in just four steps: identify the vehicle, find the spare part, create a quote and generate it.
The ease of use is a key element of these systems, especially for convincing older professionals who are more or less reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1 034 vehicles, including 666 passenger cars, 109 off-road vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, to use it, a computer and an Internet connection are required.
Once the model to be repaired has been identified by its chassis number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and the required part is selected.
The user can include variables such as labour price, increases or reductions, and then print the quote to deliver to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a catalogue of references.
The main difference between these two systems is that the system for garages does not include estimated man-hours.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is 350 euros per year, which can be credited.
Audatex is currently working on making these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics are very happy about, since it will allow, for example, to select a door and turn it to see the inside.
